<subSubSection id="37E2657C4F3DFFE8F0FAFB88FA9A6D1F" pageId="16" pageNumber="15" type="description">
<paragraph id="7F4736F74F3DFFE8F0FAFB88FA9A6D1F" blockId="16.[192,1440,1059,1340]" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">
This species was previously regarded as the most widespread halictine species in the New World, however recent electrophoretic and molecular analyses have shown that two species are involved (
<bibRefCitation id="1B694B064F3DFFE8F537FB68FE1F6C9F" author="Carman G. M. &amp; L. Packer" pageId="16" pageNumber="15" pagination="168 - 176" refId="ref11284" refString="Carman G. M., and L. Packer. 1997. A cryptic species allied to Halictus ligatus Say (Hymenoptera: Halictidae) detected by allozyme electrophoresis. Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society 69: 168 - 176." type="journal article" year="1997">Carman and Packer 1997</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="1B694B064F3DFFE8F19FFB48FD1A6C9F" author="Danforth, B. N. &amp; P. L. Mitchell &amp; L. Packer" box="[405,655,1187,1211]" pageId="16" pageNumber="15" pagination="387 - 391" refId="ref12063" refString="Danforth, B. N., P. L. Mitchell, and L. Packer. 1998. Mitochondrial DNA differentiation between two cryptic Halictus (Hymenoptera: Halictidae) species. Annals of the Entomological Society of America 91: 387 - 391." type="journal article" year="1998">Danforth et al., 1998</bibRefCitation>
). The Caribbean species is 
<taxonomicName id="B8F84D744F3DFFE8F3C5FB48FB6E6C9F" authority="Lepeletier" authorityName="Lepeletier. However, Wolcott" authorityYear="1948" box="[975,1275,1187,1211]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Halictus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="poeyi">
<emphasis id="4D8CEAE54F3DFFE8F3C5FB48FBEF6C9F" box="[975,1146,1187,1211]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">Halictus poeyi</emphasis>
Lepeletier
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="1B694B064F3DFFE8F502FB48FECC6CFF" author="Carman G. M. &amp; L. Packer" pageId="16" pageNumber="15" pagination="168 - 176" refId="ref11284" refString="Carman G. M., and L. Packer. 1997. A cryptic species allied to Halictus ligatus Say (Hymenoptera: Halictidae) detected by allozyme electrophoresis. Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society 69: 168 - 176." type="journal article" year="1997">Carman and Packer 1997</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="1B694B064F3DFFE8F169FB28FD946CFF" author="Genaro, J. A." box="[355,513,1219,1243]" pageId="16" pageNumber="15" pagination="247 - 254" refId="ref13153" refString="Genaro, J. A. 2007. Las abejas (Hymenoptera: Apoidea: Anthophila) de la Hispaniola, Antillas. Boletin de la Sociedad Entomologica Aragonesa, Espana 40: 247 - 254." type="journal article" year="2007">Genaro 2007</bibRefCitation>
; L. Packer and J. A. Genaro, unpublished data). 
<bibRefCitation id="1B694B064F3DFFE8F442FB28FA986CFF" author="Ashmead, W. H." box="[1096,1293,1219,1243]" pageId="16" pageNumber="15" pagination="207 - 367" refId="ref11046" refString="Ashmead, W. H. 1900. Report upon the aculeate Hymenoptera of the Islands of St. Vincent and Grenada, with additions to the parasitic Hymenoptera and a list of the described Hymenoptera of the West Indies. Transactions of the Entomological Society of London 1900: 207 - 367." type="journal article" year="1900">Ashmead (1900)</bibRefCitation>
recorded 
<taxonomicName id="B8F84D744F3DFFE8F588FB2FFE836CDF" authorityName="Say" authorityYear="1837" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Halictus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ligatus">
<emphasis id="4D8CEAE54F3DFFE8F588FB2FFE836CDF" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">H. ligatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as occurring in 
<collectingCountry id="07EF76674F3DFFE8F1D7FB0FFDE46CDF" box="[477,625,1251,1275]" name="Puerto Rico" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">Puerto Rico</collectingCountry>
, under the synonym 
<taxonomicName id="B8F84D744F3DFFE8F37FFB0FFA0A6CDF" authority="Lepeletier. However, Wolcott (1948)" authorityName="Lepeletier. However, Wolcott" authorityYear="1948" box="[885,1439,1251,1275]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Halictus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="poeyi">
<emphasis id="4D8CEAE54F3DFFE8F37FFB0FFC4C6CDF" box="[885,985,1252,1275]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">H. poeyi</emphasis>
Lepeletier. However, 
<bibRefCitation id="1B694B064F3DFFE8F4E6FB08FA0A6CDF" author="Wolcott, G. N." box="[1260,1439,1251,1275]" pageId="16" pageNumber="15" pagination="749 - 975" refId="ref16709" refString="Wolcott, G. N. 1948. The insects of Puerto Rico. Hymenoptera. Journal of Agriculture of the University of Puerto Rico 32: 749 - 975." type="journal article" year="1948">Wolcott (1948)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
expressed the view that 
<taxonomicName id="B8F84D744F3DFFE8F1E0FAEFFDD86D3F" authorityName="Lepeletier. However, Wolcott" authorityYear="1948" box="[490,589,1284,1307]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Halictus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="poeyi">
<emphasis id="4D8CEAE54F3DFFE8F1E0FAEFFDD86D3F" box="[490,589,1284,1307]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">H. poeyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as listed by Ashmead is actuality one of the 
<taxonomicName id="B8F84D744F3DFFE8F467FAE8FA356D3F" authority="" box="[1133,1440,1283,1307]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Lasioglossum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Dialictus">
<emphasis id="4D8CEAE54F3DFFE8F467FAE8FA836D3F" box="[1133,1302,1283,1307]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">Lasioglossum</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="4D8CEAE54F3DFFE8F52FFAE8FA356D3F" box="[1317,1440,1283,1307]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="15">Dialictus)</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species listed above. In absence of evidence to the contrary, we accept Wolcott’s conclusions.
</paragraph>
